  "text": "One main limitation to this study mentioned above, AIS was not classified into subtypes using TOAST classification (such as cardio-embolic, small-vessel, or large artery atherothrombotic strokes). Further investigations should classify AIS into these subtypes and determine if there is an association between LDs and these subtypes. This would be able to determine if theory that LDs cause the less severe small-vessel strokes is correct, and thus is the reason why we see better AIS-outcomes and reduced complications with LDs. Another limitation of the study was LDs were identified as a secondary diagnosis (history of LDs or first-time diagnosis) responsible for AIS and we did not have data on statin use prior or during the hospitalization. So neuroprotective role of statin [CITATION_1] was difficult to differentiate. Other limitations to this study include the fact that we only considered patients who were hospitalized with strokes; between 10%-40% of stroke patients are not admitted to the in-patient hospital [CITATION_2] . Thus, patients with less severe strokes may not be included in this study. The outcomes evaluated while patients were in hospital and status of patients on discharge, we had not evaluated the long-term outcomes. Additionally, although co-morbidities were accounted for and adjusted for in analysis, other subtler differences between patients such as prior strokes or other unaccounted medications may flaw our design outcomes. Though we had adjusted outcomes model with antiplatelets or anticoagulant use before and during hospitalization, but we had no record on statin use to adjust the models.",
